description.value:
c. 2 AD: Paul is born into the tribe of Benjamin and given the name Saul.

Phillipians 3:5 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Phil%203:5&version=KJV)Acts 21:39, 22:3 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2021:39,%2022:3&version=KJV)


36-40 AD: Paul stays home for 3 years after fleeing Jeruslaem. He leaves when summoned by Barnabus to help with the church at Antioch.
Acts 11:12-26 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2011:25-26&version=KJV)

12-15 AD: 10-year-old Saul studies under Gamaliel to eventually become a Pharisee.
Acts 22:3 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2022:3&version=KJV)
32 AD: When he reaches the age of 30, he consents to and witnesses the death of Stephen, the first Christian martyr. Saul then leads persecution against the earliest Christians.
Acts 7:58-8:4 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%207:58-8:4&version=KJV)
36 AD: Paul spends 15 days preaching, but the people do not believe he is a disciple until Barnbus vouches for him. His life is again threatened and he is taken to Caesarea then home to Tarsus.
Acts 9:26-30 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%209:26-30&version=KJV)
42-44 AD: Famine strikes Judea, prompting Christians to plant and grow food to help. Paul and Barnabus bring needed relief to Jerusalem.
Acts 11:28-30 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2011:28-30&version=KJV)
49 AD: A conference is held in Jerusalem to discuss the issue of circumcision for Gentiles. Paul and Barnbus meet with James, Peter, and John first (Galatians 2:4-10 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Galatians%202:4-10&version=KJV)) and then with the entire church. They decide that Gentiles need not be circumcised and Paul brings this message back to Antioch along with Barnabus, Silas, and others.
Acts 15:1-30 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2015:1-30&version=KJV)
58 AD: A riot breaks out upon the accusation that Paul has brought a Gentile into the temple area. Roman soldiers save him from death by arresting him. His defense before the Sanhedrin gets nowhere, so soldiers escort him to Caesarea to have his case heard by Felix.
Acts 21:27-23:35 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2021:27-23:35&version=KJV)

33 AD: On his way to Damascus to arrest and punish Christians there, he sees a light from Heaven. Jesus asks: "Saul, Saul, why persecutest thou me?" This experience causes Paul's conversion. He is struck blind and carried to Damascus by his companions.
In Damascus, Ananias heals his blindness. After this, he is baptized, recieves the Holy Spirit, and begins preaching the Gospel under threat of death. This threat forces him to flee to Arabia.
Acts 9:1-24 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%209:1-24&version=KJV)
36 AD: Paul stops in Damascus on his way back from Arabia to Jerusalem.
Galatians 1:17 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=gal%201:17&version=KJV)

33-36 AD: Paul spends 3 years in Arabia where he learns "by the revelation of Jesus Christ."
Galatians 1:11-12 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=gal%201:11-12&version=KJV)

36 AD: Paul makes a brief stop in Caesarea on his way back from Jerusalem to Tarsus.
Acts 9:30 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%209:30&version=KJV)
58-60 AD: Paul spends two years as a Roman prisoner, defending himself on three different occasions. He eventually appeals his case to Caesar rather than risk death by returning to Jerusalem.
Acts 24-26 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2024-26&version=KJV)

41 AD: Barnabus brings Paul to Antioch, where the disciples were first called Christians, to preach for a year.
Acts 11:25-26 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2011:25-26&version=KJV)
44 AD: After bringing relief to the famine in Jerusalem, Paul begins his first missionary journey in Antioch along with Barnabus and John-Mark.
Acts 12:25, 13:1-4 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2012:25,%2013:1-4&version=KJV)
46-49 AD:When Barnabus and Paul return from their first missionary journey, they stay in Antioch for 3 years to preach and share the results of their journey. Upon their return from the Jerusalem conference some time that year, they have a conflict regarding whether or not to take John-Mark on their next journey. Paul then takes Silas back through the cities previously visited while Barnabus and John-Mark head to Cypress.
Acts 14:26-28, 15:36-41 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2014:26-28,%2015:36-41&version=KJV)
52-53 AD: During a brief stay between his second and third missionary journeys, Paul publicly corrects Peter, Barnabus, and others who withdraw from Gentile converts. During this time, he also writes his epistle to the Galatians.
Galatians 2:11-20 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Galatians%202:11-20&version=KJV)

44-46 AD: Paul goes on his first missionary journey.
Acts 13:4-14:26 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2013:4-14:26&version=KJV)

49-52 AD: Paul goes on his second missionary journey.
Acts 16:1-18:22 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2016:1-18:22&version=KJV)

properties.name: Paul's Third Missionary Journey
properties.description: 53-57 AD: Paul goes on his third missionary journey, ending in Jerusalem.

description.value:
60-61 AD: Paul is taken to Rome as a prisoner.
Acts 27-28:13 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%2027-28:13&version=KJV)

61-63 AD: Despite being a prisoner, Paul is able to recieve visitors and continue preaching the Gospel. He also manages to write Ephesians, Phillippians, Colossians, Philemon, 1 Timothy, Titus, and probably even Hebrews. He is set free in 63 AD and heads to Crete.
Acts 28:16-31 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=ACts%2028:16-31&version=KJV)
67-68 AD: Paul is taken prisoner again. He writes his last epistle to Timothy before dying as a martyr under the hand of Nero.
2 Timothy (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=2%20Timothy&version=KJV)

63 AD: Upon being set free from prison, Paul heads to Crete and then to Nicoplois in Macedonia.
Titus 1:5 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=titus%201:5&version=KJV), Titus 3:12 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=titus%203:12&version=KJV)

63 AD: Upon being set free from prison, Paul heads to Crete and then to Nicoplois in Macedonia.
Titus 1:5 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=titus%201:5&version=KJV), Titus 3:12 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=titus%203:12&version=KJV)

64-67 AD: Paul visits Christians in Spain.
Romans 15:27-29 (http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Romans%2015:27-29&version=KJV)
